10337nam a22012255i 9783110662085DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106620857 a10.1515/97831106620852doi  a(DE-B1597)522037  a(OCoLC)1191863585  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aART0590002bisacsh0484pa060qDE-10100aSocializing Art Museums :bRethinking the Publics' Experience /ced. by Alejandra Alonso Tak, Ángel Pazos-López. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENT -- tTo Open up Art Museums to a More Social Approach: An Introduction -- tMUSEUMS AND AUDIENCES IN THE 21ST CENTURY -- tMuseums in a Globalized World. Still in the Service of Society? -- tBest Practices in Visitors Studies. The Permanent Laboratory of Museum Audiences -- tTransformations in Museums from the Audience’s Perception -- tFrom the Public Museum to the Virtual Museum. Communication in the Museum in Digital Environments. The Spanish Situation -- tSeducing Audiences. Empathy Marketing Signs in the Centro Botín -- tEDUCATION STRATEGIES IN MUSEUMS -- tBorder Pedagogy and Empowerment Education in Museums -- tAccessible Museums: Vision or Reality? The Impact of Belgian Museum Education on Society -- tMuseum at Home. Engaging New Audiences through the Sphere of Domesticity -- tMUSEUMS AS FORUMS FOR CITIZENSHIP -- tNew York City’s Art Museums and Activism. From Early-Twentieth-Century Antifascism to the Post-Occupy Condition -- tThe Museum as a Potential Space. An Approach to Trauma and Emotional Memory in the Museum -- tMuseums and Violence Against Women. Raising Awareness of Symbolic Violence -- tThe Inclusion of Vulnerable Groups in University Museums. The Case of the Complutense University of Madrid -- tACCESSIBILITY IN MUSEUMS -- tResearch Strategies in Inclusive Museology with the Museo del Prado Collections. Towards Universal Accessibility, Sensoriality, and Social Integration -- tClose Your Eyes and Open Your Mind. A Practice-Based Experiment of Cultural Mediation for Visually Impaired People -- tThe Museum as a Space for Individual and Collective Expression. An Intervention Involving Individuals with Asperger Syndrome or High Functioning Autism -- tRETHINKING SPACES IN MUSEUMS -- tMuseums of the Void. The Exhibition Space as Empty Signifier -- tThe 3.0 Showcase. The Smart Glass as an Interactive Support -- tFinal Reflections on the Laboratory for Museographical Research and Experimentation. Museums: In Search of a New Typology -- tAUTHORS -- tIMAGE CREDITS -- tPLATES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArt museums today face the challenge of opening themselves up as institutions to a changing society. This publication offers new perspectives on museological trends that are developing in various countries and cultures. Through increasingly flexible, inclusive and unexpected museum typologies, institutions aim to give their visitors greater access to art. The essays define the role of the museum as a medium of social change, as a protagonist in an education process and as a technologically innovative platform. Art historians, but also practitioners from the museum world – including curators, architects and psychologists – examine what is expected of art museums using case studies and against the background of the humanities and social sciences.  aKunstmuseen stehen heute vor der Herausforderung, sich als Institutionen einer sich wandelnden Gesellschaft zu öffnen. Diese Publikation bietet neue Perspektiven auf museologische Trends, die sich in verschiedenen Ländern und Kulturen entwickeln. Durch zunehmend flexible, integrative und unerwartete Museumstypologien wollen die Institutionen ihren Besuchern einen besseren Zugang zur Kunst ermöglichen. Die Essays definieren die Rolle des Museums als Medium des sozialen Wandels, als Protagonist in einem Bildungsprozess und als technologisch innovative Plattform. Kunsthistoriker, aber auch Praktiker aus der Museumswelt - darunter Kuratoren, Architekten und Psychologen - untersuchen anhand von Fallstudien und vor dem Hintergrund der Geistes- und Sozialwissenschaften, was von Kunstmuseen erwartet wird.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 4aKunstinstitution. 4aMuseologie. 4aRezeption. 7aART / Museum Studies.2bisacsh  amuseography, museology, art public.1 aAlonso Tak, Alejandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlonso Tak, Alejandra, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAyala, Íñigo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBueno Doral, Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCandeloro, Jean-Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuenca, Jaime, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuenca-Amigo, Macarena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEwa Majewska, Martyna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernández Cao, Marián López, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallardo López, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGesché-Koning, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález Hernando, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinz, Hans-Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIdoate Pérez, Silbia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrimia, Alexandra, econtr